Learning Goals

  • understand the capabilities and disadvantages of R Markdown documents
  • learn the structure and syntax of R Markdown documents
  • produce and customize the appearance of R output
  • compile your R Markdown documents into PDFs, HTML documents, and slide presentations

You should have:

  • installation of R
  • installation of R Studio
  • installation of the tidyverse suite of R packages
  • installation of the tinytex R package
  • some familiarity with R would help, but isn’t strictly necessary

What is R Markdown?

What is R Markdown?

R Markdown is a document format that lets you mix text and R code and output.

From an R Markdown file (.Rmd), you can create PDFs, webpages, slide presentations, etc.

Example uses

In my own work:

  • keeping research notes
  • completing assignments
  • writing papers

Other uses:

  • personal websites (via blogdown package)
  • creating interactive tutorials (via learnr package)
  • entire books
  • websites

ok, but why?

  1. Keep code, figures, and text in one place (no more copy and pasting)
  2. Lends well to meaningful reproducibility
  3. Versatile – variety of outputs, and you don’t even need to use R!

It can’t be all good…

  1. Custom formatting is more difficult
  2. Learning curve is steeper than word processors
  3. Need R + R Studio to edit (which collaborators may not have)

A brief note on getting oriented in R Studio

Editor (default top left panel) - where you edit scripts, files Console (bottom left panel) - an active session of R Top right panel - workflow helpers (e.g. objects in environment, Git) Bottom right panel - viewer, and help panel

Getting set up

  1. Open R Studio

(1.5. Set working directory (Session -> Set Working Directory))

  1. File -> New -> R Markdown… (accept defaults)
  2. A new tab should open in your editor

That’s it! This is an R Markdown file!

“Knit” the file using the Knit button near the top.

Components of an R Markdown file

A couple key components:

  1. header
  2. text
  3. code “chunks”

The header

The header contains metadata about the document:

  • title, author, date (as character strings)
  • output: the desired format – most common would be pdf_document or html_document

Text

“Markdown” is actually a specific text format (used outside of this context).

The key idea is that it’s similar to plain text, and formatting is simple. We’ll come back to this later.

Code chunks

Code chunks contain R code, and are written like this:

```{r}
1 + 1
```
2

These code chunks are evaluated when you knit the Rmd, and the result appears in the output.

Code chunks

Actually, code chunks don’t need to be R code! You can replace r with python to evaluate Python code, or use other engines (I don’t have experience here)

```{python}
1 + 1
```

Making text richer

We want more from our text editors/word processors. In particular, things like: section headers, bolding, italics, links, equations

Headers

Headers are preceded by #

# big title

## small title

### even smaller title

some text

Text formatting

  • bolding: **some bold text**
  • italics: *some italic text*
  • links: [link text](https://www.utoronto.ca/)
  • equations (inline:) $y = mx + b$

Text formatting

  • bold text

Citations

  • need a BibTeX .bib file
  • put the path to the bib file in header bibliography: my_references.bib
  • add “References” as a section at the end of your document

You can find BibTeX entries using Google Scholar, or citation managers usually have a way to export.

Plots (and other R output)

R output will show up automatically.

Can adjust behaviour via “chunk options”: e.g. whether to evaluate the code, whether to show the code, whether to hide output

Chunk options

Set the option globally for the document in the first chunk:

knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = FALSE)

For a specific chunk:

```{r, echo = FALSE}
1 + 1
```

Chunk options

  • echo = TRUE (default): print the code in the final document
  • eval = TRUE (default): evaluate the chunk
  • include = TRUE (default): evaluate the chunk and show code and output (if FALSE, hide code and output)
  • results = 'markup': show (formatted) results (if 'hide')
  • warning = TRUE(default): print warning messages

Chunk options

e.g. If I want to show code, but not evaluate the result:

```{r, echo = TRUE, eval = FALSE}
1 + 1
```

Tables

Data tables in R are usually dataframes.

data.frame(x = 1:2, y = 3:4)
##   x y
## 1 1 3
## 2 2 4

To make a table look nicer, use knitr::kable()

x y
1 3
2 4

  • output: ioslides_presentation

Lists

  • this

  * lists
  • multi-level…
    • lists

Include a table of contents

output:
  pdf_document:
    toc: true

adjust with toc_depth: option

Evaluate code in-line

Write “20 + pi is approximately `r 20+pi`”

Appears as: “20 + pi is approximately 23.1415927.”

Evaluate code in-line (use case)

Create dynamic text that depends on the analysis in your code.

There have been `r n_vaccinations` vaccine doses administered in Ontario, which corresponds to `r n_vaccinations/population` doses per capita, or `r n_vaccinations/population * 100000` per 100k people.

evaluates to:

There have been 500 vaccine doses administered in some place, which corresponds to 0.005 doses per capita, or 500 per 100k people.

Customizing figure output

Figure captions with fig.cap= code chunk option

Figure size with fig.width= and fig.height= code chunk options (default unit is inches)

Workflow tips/quirks

  • handling directories

R Markdown always runs from the directory of the .Rmd file – not the working directory.

For big projects, I’d recommend the here package, so that directories point to the “base” project directory

Workflow tips/quirks

  • collapsing and running code chunks (demo)
  • R Markdown runs code in a new environment (demo)

Beyond the basics

Programatic generation of reports

Generate (possibly many) reports from a script

In header:

params:
  param_name1: param1_value
  param_name2: param2_value

In R:

rmarkdown::render("path/to/file.Rmd", params = ...)

Programmatic generation of reports

Possible use cases

  1. A report is automatically generated at the end of a script
  2. Repeat the same analysis for multiple similar datasets

Maps

In HTML, you can include (interactive) maps using leaflet, and other R mapping packages.

library(leaflet)

leaflet() %>% addTiles() %>%
  addPopups(-79.39967927305904, 43.66457135213694, "Robarts Library")
